{{COI|date=October 2018}} <!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Wall Street Journal photo of Najat Kaanache at 2013 World Science Festival in NY.jpg|thumbnail|right|Wall Street Journal photo of Najat Kaanache plating her "Genius Apple" dish at the 2013 World Science Festival in NYC{{deletable image-caption|Thursday, 11 May 2017|F7}}]] --> [[File:Food Magic with Najat Kaanache and Bill Yosses.jpg|thumb|right|Chef Najat Kaanache with White House Executive Pastry Chef Bill Yosses lecturing at Harvard University]] '''Najat Kaanache''' is the host of AMC Networks' cooking series "Cocina Marroqui" which airs on Canal Cocina in Spain and El Gourmet throughout 20 countries in Latin America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canalcocina.es/programa/cocina-marroqui|title=Cocina Marroqui|author=Canal Cocina|work=canalcocina.es|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> Kaanache was born and raised in [[San Sebastián]] of Spain's [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]]. She gained fame as a lead actress on Spanish daytime television series "Goenkale" and then traveled throughout the Middle East and South America working in philanthropy to empower women and street kids. She later attended culinary school and gained fame as "The Pilgrim Chef" by blogging throughout her four years training with the world's top chefs: [[Ferran Adria]], [[Rene Redzepi]], [[Thomas Keller]], [[Grant Achatz]], [[Heston Blumenthal]] and [[Martín Berasategui]].
After spending two years working as an apprentice in the kitchens at Chicago's [[Alinea (restaurant)|Alinea]], Napa's [[The French Laundry]], New York's [[Per Se (restaurant)]], and Copenhagen's [[Noma (restaurant)]] Kaanache went on to achieve the auspicious Executive and Creative Haute Cuisine Certification after completing her apprenticeship during the final two seasons at Spain's [[elBulli]]. [[Ferran Adria]] stated to the Maghreb Arabe Presse that "Najat Kaanache represents the soul of [[Morocco]] through the language of the kitchen. Her passion for creativity and innovation should be a reference for the country."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hespress.com/marocains-du-monde/62783.html|title=نجاة كعناش .. علامَة دولية في فنّ الطّبخ|author=Bouchra Benyoussef|work=hespress.com|accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thepleasuresofthepalate.blogspot.com/2015/03/najat-kaanache-girl-who-dreamed-of.html|title=Savoir Faire|author=Enriqueta E. Lemoine|work=thepleasuresofthepalate|accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref> After El Bulli's historic closure, Kaanache traveled extensively to instruct chefs across the globe <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cychefs.com/article/en/498/el-bulli-official-world-tour-stop-in-cyprus|title=Cy Chefs|work=Cy Chefs|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> in the latest gastronomic techniques and taught and lectured alongside White House Executive Pastry Chef, [[Bill Yosses]] on the science of cooking at Harvard University (pictured), New York University and at the 2013 World Science Festival in NYC (pictured) and 2013 Beijing Science Festival in China.
She was the opening chef partner of Souk Restaurant in Dallas, TX.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sidedish.dmagazine.com/2013/09/04/najat-kaanache-partners-with-yaser-khalaf-souk-at-trinity-groves-is-their-first-project/|title=Najat Kaanache|work=SideDish|accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref> She was the opening chef partner of Piripi Restaurant in the Village of Merrick Park in Coral Gables, FL;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/restaurants/piripi-brings-a-bit-of-spain-to-merrick-park-sangria-magic-mushrooms-and-lobster-paella-photos-7567199|title=Najat Kaanache|work=Miami New Times|accessdate=9 October 2015}}</ref> She is the chef and owner of [[Nur Restaurant]], in the Medina of Fez, Morocco.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nur.ma/|title=NUR|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>
