{{refimprove|date=December 2014}} {{Undue|date=April 2011}} {{Infobox music genre |name=Nazi punk |stylistic_origins={{hlist|[[Hardcore punk]]|[[punk rock]]|[[Oi!]]|[[white power music]]}} |cultural_origins=Late 1970s, [[United Kingdom]] |instruments={{hlist|[[Vocals]]|[[guitar]]|[[bass guitar|bass]]|[[drums]]}} |subgenres=[[Rock Against Communism]] |fusiongenres= |regional_scenes= |other_topics={{hlist|[[Neo-Nazism]]|[[white power skinhead]]|[[National Socialist black metal]]}} |bgcolor=crimson |color=white |popularity=Underground following among [[white power skinhead]]s, [[neo-Nazism|neo-Nazis]] and their sympathizers }} {{Nazism sidebar}} A '''Nazi punk''' is a [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]] who is part of the [[punk subculture]]. The term also describes the related music genre,<ref>Wallace, Amy. ''The Official Punk Rock Book of Lists.'' Backbeat Books, 2007. p. 186</ref> which is sometimes also referred to as '''hatecore'''. Nazi Punk music generally sounds like other forms of [[punk rock]], but differs by having lyrics that express hatred of some [[Minority groups|ethnic minorities]], [[Jews]], [[homosexuality |homosexuals]],[[anarchism| anarchists]], and other perceived enemies.
It is a subgenre of punk that contrasts sharply with the [[anti-authoritarianism|anti-authoritarian]] ideas prevalent in much of the punk subculture. While early punks including [[Sid Vicious]] and [[Siouxsie Sioux]] incorporated Nazi imagery such as [[Swastika|Swastikas]], this has commonly been interpreted as an attempt to shock, rather than as a genuine belief in principles of Nazism. In the long-standing band [[The Exploited]], [[Wattie Buchan]] has been regularly questioned about his swastika tattoo and he has constantly denied being a racist.<ref name=Documentary>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aJj6x0neC7E Documentary on the history of the band The Exploited</ref>
In 1978 in [[United Kingdom|Britain]], the [[White nationalism|white nationalist]] [[National Front (United Kingdom)|National Front]] had a punk-oriented youth organization called the Punk Front.<ref>Reynolds, Simon. ''Rip It Up and Start Again: Postpunk 1978-1984.'' Penguin (Non-Classics), 2006. p. 65</ref> Although the Punk Front only lasted one year, it recruited several [[English people|English]] punks, as well as forming a number of [[White supremacy|white power]] punk bands such as The Dentists, The Ventz, Tragic Minds and White Boss.<ref>Reynolds, Simon, ''Rip It Up and Start Again: Postpunk 1978-1984'' (Penguin (Non-Classics), 2006), p. 65</ref><ref>Sabin, Roger, ''Punk Rock: So What?: The Cultural Legacy of Punk.'' (Routledge, 1999), pp. 207-208.</ref> In the early 1980s, the [[white power skinhead]] band Brutal Attack temporarily transformed into a Nazi punk band.<ref>[http://www.detour-records.co.uk/STRAPS.htm "The Straps: History"]</ref> They said they did that in the hopes of getting public concerts booked easier, but this tactic did not work, and they soon returned to being a racist skinhead band.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
The Nazi Punk subculture appeared in the [[United States]] by the early 1980s in the [[hardcore punk]] scene.<ref>Andersen, Mark. ''Dance of Days: Two Decades of Punk in the Nation's Capital.'' Akashic Books, 2003. p. 159</ref><ref>Flynn, Michael. ''Globalizing the Streets.'' Columbia University Press, 2008. p. 191</ref>
== See also == * [[List of neo-Nazi bands]] * [[National Socialist black metal]] * [[Nazi chic]] * [[Nipster]] * [[Punk ideologies]] * [[Rock Against Communism]] * [[White nationalism]]
